    var opts = new CimOperationOptions();
    opts.SetCustomOption(&quot;LocalAddress&quot;, new string[] { &quot;192.168.1.0/24&quot; }, CimType.StringArray, false);
    opts.SetCustomOption(&quot;RemoteAddress&quot;, new string[] { &quot;10.10.1.115/24&quot; }, CimType.StringArray, false);
    var cimSession = CimSession.Create(computerName: null); // null means to use the local computer
    cimSession.CreateInstance(&quot;root/standardcimv2&quot;, ipSecRule, opts);

Obviously it is matching up the keys &quot;LocalAddress&quot; and &quot;RemoteAddress&quot; to the properties on the `MSFT_NetAddressFilter`.  But what if the key exists on multiple spawned objects?  Is there a syntax for declaring which to set?  Like `opts.SetCustomOption(&quot;ObjectName::PropertyName&quot;)` or the like? (I guessed at a few of those, but had no luck.)

I&#39;ve tried digging through standards, cmdlets, decompiled code (Microsoft.Management.Infrastructure.CimCmdlets.dll, Microsoft.Management.Infrastrucutre.dll, Microsoft.Windows.Firewall.Commands.dll) and haven&#39;t figured it out.

`Microsoft.Windows.Firewall.Commands.DAPolicyChange.ProcessRecord()` actually uses `CimOperationOptions` for invoking a the 
`MSFT_NetConSecRule.SyncPolicyDelta()` method; but tracking that through the code I ended at `Microsoft.Management.Infrastructure.Native.&lt;Module&gt;.MI_Session_Invoke`, at which point I was lost.

**tldr;** I have code that works when I provide `CimOperationOptions` but I do not know what `CimOperationOptions` are actually for/how they are applied.  So I don&#39;t know when I&#39;ll need them in the future.

